# Result in std::io - Rust

## Type Alias [std](../index.html)::[io](index.html)::[Result](#)

1.0.0 ¬∑ [source](about:blank/src/std/io/error.rs.html#54) ¬∑

```
pub type Result<T> = Result<T, Error>;
```

Expand description

A specialized [`Result`](../result/enum.Result.html "enum std::result::Result") type for I/O operations.

This type is broadly used across [`std::io`](index.html "mod std::io") for any operation which may produce an error.

This typedef is generally used to avoid writing out [`io::Error`](struct.Error.html "struct std::io::Error") directly and is otherwise a direct mapping to [`Result`](../result/enum.Result.html "enum std::result::Result").

While usual Rust style is to import types directly, aliases of [`Result`](../result/enum.Result.html "enum std::result::Result") often are not, to make it easier to distinguish between them. [`Result`](../result/enum.Result.html "enum std::result::Result") is generally assumed to be [`std::result::Result`](../result/enum.Result.html "enum std::result::Result"), and so users of this alias will generally use `io::Result` instead of shadowing the [prelude](../prelude/index.html "mod std::prelude")‚Äôs import of [`std::result::Result`](../result/enum.Result.html "enum std::result::Result").

## [¬ß](#examples)Examples

A convenience function that bubbles an `io::Result` to its caller:

```
use std::io;

fn get_string() -> io::Result<String> {
    let mut buffer = String::new();

    io::stdin().read_line(&mut buffer)?;

    Ok(buffer)
}
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++use+std::io;%0A++++%0A++++fn+get_string()+-%3E+io::Result%3CString%3E+%7B%0A++++++++let+mut+buffer+=+String::new();%0A++++%0A++++++++io::stdin().read_line(%26mut+buffer)?;%0A++++%0A++++++++Ok(buffer)%0A++++%7D%0A%7D&edition=2021)

```
enum Result<T> {
    Ok(T),
    Err(Error),
}
```

[¬ß](#variant.Ok)1.0.0

Contains the success value

[¬ß](#variant.Err)1.0.0

Contains the error value

